ğŸŸ¡ Level 2 â€” Character classes, boundaries, and groups
9.	Match a word boundary â€œcatâ€ (whole word only).
Example: "cat" âœ… "concatenate" âŒ
    (cat)
10.	Match a string that is a valid hexadecimal color code (like #A1B2C3).
Example: #FFF, #12ab90 âœ…
    ^#[a-zA-Z0-9]{3,6}
11.	Match a string containing an email-like pattern (simplified).
Example: "abc@xyz.com" âœ… "abc.com" âŒ
    ^[a-z]+@[a-z]+\.[a-z]+
12.	Match a date in dd/mm/yyyy format (basic, no validation).
Example: "23/09/2025" âœ… "3/9/25" âŒ
    \d{2}/\d{2}/\d{4}
13.	Match strings that have consecutive repeated letters (e.g. "book", "mississippi").
Example: "balloon" âœ… "cat" âŒ
    ^[a-z].*[a-z]{2}[a-z].*
14.	Match a string that has at least one digit and one letter.
Example: "abc123" âœ… "123" âŒ
    (?=.*[a-z])(?=.*\d).+,    // at least one char (?=.*[a-z]), at least one digit (?=.*\d), .+ repeat string itself may be
15.	Match a string that is a valid username (start with a letter, 3â€“15 chars, may contain _).
Example: "a_user1" âœ… "1user" âŒ
    ^[a-zA-Z]_.*[a-zA-Z0-9]{3,15}
16.	Match a valid filename ending with .txt or .csv.
Example: "report.csv" âœ… "file.txt" âœ… "file.doc" âŒ
    ^.*[a-zA-Z]\.(txt|csv)   \\   single \ is ending with
